{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ef8eccd1-1240-4195-9216-f3daba765cc8","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for **Apple crash reports** in:\n\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS). Open them with any text editor.\n\n**Other options:**\n\n1. **`lldb`** — attach post-mortem or run under it:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./YourApp\n   ```\n2. **Core dumps** — macOS disables them by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   Cores land at the path you set.\n\n3. **Console.app** — search for your app name to find system-level crash logs.\n\nThe `.ips` crash report includes the crashing thread, backtrace, and signal info — usually enough to start debugging without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7eca6809-6346-4882-b700-87a377f1c64a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":294,"requestId":"D81A:CE960:60035B7:67EE817:69FBEFE1"},"id":"c9a6db90-504d-4adf-8d9a-509ac2ecbf6e","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:50:34.113Z","parentId":"c6311471-b419-47d0-b8c5-d3e1ac06c4af"}
